<BaseLayout title="Projects" description="Paul Platzer — Projects">
  <h1>Projects</h1>

  <h2>DYNADIST-NA</h2>

  <p>
    I am the principal investigator of the project{' '}
    <strong>DYNADIST-NA</strong>: Dynamical distance optimization for
    basin-scale North Atlantic sea-surface temperature jump predictability.
    This project has two main goals:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>
      improve our understanding of oceanic drivers of basin-scale marine
      heatwaves (MHWs) such as the summer 2023 North-Atlantic event,
    </li>
    <li>
      develop a new methodology for optimizing distances in analog methods,
      especially forecasting sea-surface temperatures.
    </li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    Existing analysis of the basin-scale North-Atlantic MHW of summer 2023 are
    mostly limited to atmospheric drivers (e.g. England et al., 2025). As a
    sister project of PORC-&#201;PIC, DYNADIST-NA aims at better
    characterizing oceanic drivers of such extreme events.
  </p>

  <figure class="project-figure">
    <img
      src="/assets/figures/north-atlantic-mhw-2023-worldview.gif"
      alt="NASA Worldview animation showing sea-surface temperature anomalies over the North Atlantic from May to August 2023"
      loading="lazy"
    />
    <figcaption>
      North Atlantic sea-surface temperature anomalies during the 2023 marine
      heatwave, May&ndash;August 2023, from the GHRSST Level 4 MUR Global Foundation
      Sea Surface Temperature Analysis (v4.1) dataset (doi:10.5067/GHGMR-4FJ04). Animation created from{' '}
      <a href="https://worldview.earthdata.nasa.gov/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">
        NASA Worldview
      </a>,
      part of NASA&rsquo;s Earth Science Data and Information System (ESDIS).
    </figcaption>
  </figure>

  <p>
    Existing methodologies for optimizing analog distances today are either
    non state-specific (Platzer et al., 2025), or use indirect optimization
    not directly tailored at forecasting scores such as CRPS (Toride et al.,
    2025). DYNADIST-NA aims at providing new algorithms for direct state-specific
    distance optimization for analog forecasting.
  </p>

  <p>
    More details on the project, including scientific literature review, can be
    found in this{' '}
    <a href="/assets/pdfs/DYNADIST_NA_Concept_Note.pdf">concept note</a>.
  </p>

  <p>
    DYNADIST-NA is supported by ISblue project, Interdisciplinary graduate
    school for the blue planet (ANR-17-EURE-0015) and co-funded by a grant
    from the French government under the program &ldquo;Investissements
    d&rsquo;Avenir&rdquo; embedded in France 2030. The funding will be used to
    support a 6-month internship, international collaborations, and a small
    seminar. More informations to come.
  </p>

